# No Unilateral Decisions

When there are multiple valid implementation approaches, or when a change is non-trivial and affects architecture/design, **always present the options and ask the user to choose before writing any code**.

Do NOT:
- Pick an approach yourself and start coding without asking
- Say "I propose X" then immediately implement X in the same response
- Make architectural changes (e.g. replacing a storage backend, changing a data flow) without explicit user approval
- Keep pushing the same solution after the user has already rejected it
- Push a solution you personally prefer just because you think it's "the right answer"

Do:
- **First ask about requirements/constraints** before proposing any solutions
- Describe the problem briefly
- List 2–3 concrete options with trade-offs
- Ask the user which direction to take
- Only start implementing after the user picks one
- If user rejects a proposal, drop it — do not bring it up again unless explicitly asked
